message_1:
Solve the following system of linear equations using block matrices:

\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}
3 & -1 & 0 \\
-1 & 2 & -1 \\
0 & -1 & 3
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix}
= 
\begin{bmatrix}
2  \\
1 \\
1 
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

Show all your steps in finding the solution.

message_2:
To solve the given system of linear equations using block matrices, we will first find the inverse of the given matrix and then multiply it with the given constant matrix to find the values of x, y, and z.

Given matrix A:

\begin{equation}
A = 
\begin{bmatrix}
3 & -1 & 0 \\
-1 & 2 & -1 \\
0 & -1 & 3
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

We will now find the inverse of matrix A. To do this, we will first find the determinant of A.

Determinant of A (|A|):

\begin{equation}
|A| = 3
\begin{vmatrix}
2 & -1 \\
-1 & 3
\end{vmatrix}
- (-1)
\begin{vmatrix}
-1 & -1 \\
0 & 3
\end{vmatrix}
+ 0
\begin{vmatrix}
-1 & 2 \\
0 & -1
\end{vmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
|A| = 3(2 * 3 - (-1) * (-1)) - (-1)(-1 * 3 - (-1) * 0) = 3(6 - 1) - 1(3) = 15 - 3 = 12
\end{equation}

Now, we will find the adjoint of matrix A (adj(A)):

\begin{equation}
adj(A) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\begin{vmatrix}
2 & -1 \\
-1 & 3
\end{vmatrix} &
-\begin{vmatrix}
-1 & -1 \\
0 & 3
\end{vmatrix} &
\begin{vmatrix}
-1 & 2 \\
0 & -1
\end{vmatrix} \\
-\begin{vmatrix}
-1 & -1 \\
0 & 3
\end{vmatrix} &
\begin{vmatrix}
3 & 0 \\
-1 & 3
\end{vmatrix} &
-\begin{vmatrix}
3 & -1 \\
-1 & 2
\end{vmatrix} \\
\begin{vmatrix}
-1 & 2 \\
0 & -1
\end{vmatrix} &
-\begin{vmatrix}
3 & -1 \\
-1 & 2
\end{vmatrix} &
\begin{vmatrix}
3 & -1 \\
-1 & 2
\end{vmatrix}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
adj(A) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
(2 * 3 - (-1) * (-1)) & -(3 - 0) & (-1 - 0) \\
-(-3) & (3 * 3 - 0) & -(6 - 1) \\
(-1 - 0) & -(6 - 1) & (6 - 1)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
adj(A) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
5 & -3 & -1 \\
3 & 9 & -5 \\
-1 & -5 & 5
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

Now, we will find the inverse of matrix A (A⁻¹):

\begin{equation}
A^{-1} = \frac{1}{|A|} adj(A) = \frac{1}{12}
\begin{bmatrix}
5 & -3 & -1 \\
3 & 9 & -5 \\
-1 & -5 & 5
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

Now, we will multiply A⁻¹ with the given constant matrix B:

\begin{equation}
B = 
\begin{bmatrix}
2  \\
1 \\
1 
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
X = A^{-1}B = \frac{1}{12}
\begin{bmatrix}
5 & -3 & -1 \\
3 & 9 & -5 \\
-1 & -5 & 5
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
2  \\
1 \\
1 
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
X = \frac{1}{12}
\begin{bmatrix}
(5 * 2) + (-3 * 1) + (-1 * 1) \\
(3 * 2) + (9 * 1) + (-5 * 1) \\
(-1 * 2) + (-5 * 1) + (5 * 1)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
X = \frac{1}{12}
\begin{bmatrix}
7 \\
10 \\
-2
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
X = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{7}{12} \\
\frac{5}{6} \\
-\frac{1}{6}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

So, the solution to the given system of linear equations is:

\begin{equation}
x = \frac{7}{12}, \quad y = \frac{5}{6}, \quad z = -\frac{1}{6}
\end{equation}
